              "      async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
              "        const element = document.querySelector('#df-19d2a190-6938-4353-b2ff-ab5a764b8ceb');\n",
              "        const dataTable =\n",
              "          await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
              "                                                    [key], {});\n",
              "        if (!dataTable) return;\n",
              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",
              "        dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
              "        await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
              "        docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
              "        element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
              "      }\n",
              "    </script>\n",

              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",

              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",

      "source": [
        "### Understanding Missing Values and Data Types\n",
        "\n",
        "From the `data.info()` output, we can see several key things:\n",
        "\n",
        "*   **Missing Values**: Columns like `multiple_deliveries`, `Time_Orderd`, `Time_Order_picked`, `Weather_conditions`, `Road_traffic_density`, and `City` have fewer non-null entries than the total number of entries (36467). This means they contain missing data that needs to be addressed.\n",
        "\n",
        "*   **Incorrect Data Types**:\n",
        "    *   `Order_Date`, `Time_Orderd`, and `Time_Order_picked` are currently `object` (string) types. To perform date and time-based calculations or analysis, these need to be converted into proper datetime objects.\n",
        "    *  `Multiple_deliveries` is `float64` (decimal numbers) but conceptually represent whole numbers (like age or count of deliveries). After handling missing values, it's good practice to convert them to `int` (integers) for better memory usage and clarity.\n",
        "\n",
        "Our next step is to address these issues: impute (fill in) missing values and convert columns to their correct data types."
      ]
    },

              "      async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
              "        const element = document.querySelector('#df-7b82b36e-8e65-4bfc-97fa-15de5cfadf2a');\n",
              "        const dataTable =\n",
              "          await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
              "                                                    [key], {});\n",
              "        if (!dataTable) return;\n",
              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",
              "        dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
              "        await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
              "        docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
              "        element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
              "      }\n",
              "    </script>\n",
              "  </div>\n",

        "# Handle inconsistent data (clean text columns : remove spaces and wrong strings)\n",
        "for col in ['Weather_conditions', 'Road_traffic_density', 'City']:\n",
        "    df[col] = df[col].astype(str).str.strip()\n",

      "source": [
        "#Handling Missing Values\n",
        "\n",
        "# Handle categorical columns\n",
        "# We'll fill missing values with the mode.\n",
        "df['Weather_conditions'].fillna(df['Weather_conditions'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
        "df['Road_traffic_density'].fillna(df['Road_traffic_density'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
        "df['City'].fillna(df['City'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "#Handle numerical columns\n",
        "df['multiple_deliveries'].fillna(df['multiple_deliveries'].median(), inplace=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Convert 'multiple_deliveries' from float to integer.\n",
        "df['multiple_deliveries'] = df['multiple_deliveries'].astype(int)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 10,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KiBG_dR53Y8h"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Calculate median age per city\n",
        "age_by_city = df.groupby('City')['Delivery_person_Age'].median()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fill missing using city median, then fill any remaining with overall median\n",
        "df['Delivery_person_Age'] = df['Delivery_person_Age'].fillna(\n",
        "    df['City'].map(age_by_city)\n",
        ").fillna(df['Delivery_person_Age'].median())\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create age groups\n",
        "df['Age_Group'] = pd.cut( df['Delivery_person_Age'], bins=[0, 25, 35, 45, 100], labels=['<25', '25-35', '35-45', '>45'])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Compute median rating per age group\n",
        "rating_by_age = df.groupby('Age_Group')['Delivery_person_Ratings'].median()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fill missing ratings using age-group median, then overall median\n",
        "df['Delivery_person_Ratings'] = (df['Delivery_person_Ratings'].fillna(df['Age_Group'].map(rating_by_age))\n",
        "    .fillna(df['Delivery_person_Ratings'].median()))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Fill missing value for Festival using mode(No)\n",
        "df['Festival'] = df['Festival'].fillna('No')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Drop temporary Age_Group column\n",
        "df.drop('Age_Group', axis=1, inplace=True)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 11,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "n2DnjaUPa12F"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Convert date & time columns\n",
        "df['Order_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Order_Date'], errors='coerce')\n",
        "df['Time_Orderd'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Time_Orderd'], errors='coerce')\n",
        "\n",
        "# Extract day of week\n",
        "df['day_of_week'] = df['Order_Date'].dt.dayofweek\n",
        "\n",
        "# Weekend flag (Saturday=5, Sunday=6)\n",
        "df['is_weekend'] = df['day_of_week'].isin([5, 6]).astype(int)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Extract hour from time\n",
        "df['order_hour'] = df['Time_Orderd'].dt.hour\n",
        "\n",
        "# Handle missing using median\n",
        "df['order_hour'].fillna(df['order_hour'].median(), inplace=True)"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 12,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "EsehbAPBI0TS"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Convert the string values into proper time (HH:MM:SS) without attaching a date\n",
        "time_col = pd.to_datetime(df['Time_Orderd'], format='%H:%M:%S', errors='coerce')\n",
        "\n",
        "#  Calculate the most frequent time value (mode)\n",
        "most_common_time = time_col.mode()[0]\n",
        "\n",
        "#  Fill missing time values with the most frequent time\n",
        "time_col = time_col.fillna(most_common_time)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Store the final column as pure time objects (without any date)\n",
        "df['Time_Orderd'] = time_col.dt.time"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "287e9d34"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Calculating Distance Between Locations (Feature Engineering)\n",
        "\n",
        "We have the latitude and longitude of both the restaurant and the delivery location. A useful feature for predicting delivery time would be the actual distance between these two points. We can calculate this using the **Haversine formula**, which computes the shortest distance over the Earth's surface, giving a 'great-circle' distance between two points.\n",
        "\n",
        "This formula is commonly used for distances on a sphere (like Earth) and is more accurate than simple Euclidean distance for points that are far apart.\n"
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "# Define the Haversine function to calculate the distance between two geographical points.\n",
        "# It takes four arguments: latitude and longitude of point 1 (lat1, lon1),\n",
        "# and latitude and longitude of point 2 (lat2, lon2).\n",
        "def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Convert all latitude and longitude values from degrees to radians.\n",
        "    # The math functions (sin, cos, etc.) in Python's 'math' module expect angles in radians.\n",
        "    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Calculate the difference in longitudes and latitudes.\n",
        "    dlon = lon2 - lon1\n",
        "    dlat = lat2 - lat1\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Apply the Haversine formula.\n",
        "    # 'a' is an intermediate calculation based on the spherical law of cosines.\n",
        "    a = sin(dlat / 2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon / 2)**2\n",
        "    # 'c' is the angular distance in radians.\n",
        "    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Earth's radius in kilometers. Used to convert angular distance to actual distance.\n",
        "    r = 6371\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Return the distance in kilometers.\n",
        "    return c * r\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply the 'haversine' function to each row of the DataFrame.\n",
        "# 'axis=1' ensures the function is applied row-wise, passing each row's values\n",
        "# for the specified columns ('Restaurant_latitude', etc.) to the 'haversine' function.\n",
        "# The calculated distance for each row is stored in a new column called 'distance_km'.\n",
        "df['distance_km'] = df.apply(lambda row: haversine(\n",
        "    row['Restaurant_latitude'],\n",
        "    row['Restaurant_longitude'],\n",
        "    row['Delivery_location_latitude'],\n",
        "    row['Delivery_location_longitude']\n",
        "), axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Display the first few rows of the relevant columns, including the newly created 'distance_km',\n",
        "# to verify the calculation.\n",
        "display(df[['Restaurant_latitude', 'Restaurant_longitude', 'Delivery_location_latitude', 'Delivery_location_longitude', 'distance_km']].head())\n",
        "df.head(10)"
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "# Handle Outliers (IQR)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Save BEFORE-handling values\n",
        "distance_before = df['distance_km'].copy()\n",
        "\n",
        "# IQR Function\n",
        "def iqr_outlier_removal(series):\n",
        "    Q1 = series.quantile(0.25)\n",
        "    Q3 = series.quantile(0.75)\n",
        "    IQR = Q3 - Q1\n",
        "    lower = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR\n",
        "    upper = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR\n",
        "    return series.clip(lower, upper)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Apply IQR Handling\n",
        "df['distance_km'] = iqr_outlier_removal(df['distance_km'])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Save AFTER-handling values\n",
        "distance_after = df['distance_km']\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot Boxplots\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Before handling\n",
        "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
        "plt.boxplot(distance_before.dropna())\n",
        "plt.title(\"Before IQR Handling\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Distance (km)\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# After handling\n",
        "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
        "plt.boxplot(distance_after.dropna())\n",
        "plt.title(\"After IQR Handling\")\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()\n"
      ]
    },

              "\n",
              "      async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
              "        const element = document.querySelector('#df-f23ede3e-5175-4f66-91d2-02d4b5a20b12');\n",
              "        const dataTable =\n",
              "          await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
              "                                                    [key], {});\n",
              "        if (!dataTable) return;\n",
              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",
              "        dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
              "        await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
              "        docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
              "        element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
              "      }\n",
              "    </script>\n",
              "  </div>\n",

        "# Create stratification bins from the original target (Time_taken)\n",
        "# These bins are ONLY used to ensure a fair and balanced train-test split.\n",
        "# They must NOT be used as model features because they leak target information\n",
        "df[\"target_bins\"] = pd.qcut(df[\"Time_taken\"], q=10, labels=False, duplicates='drop'\n",
        ")"
      ]

      "source": [
        "# Create engineered distance feature\n",
        "df['distance_km'] = df.apply(lambda row: haversine(\n",
        "    row['Restaurant_latitude'],\n",
        "    row['Restaurant_longitude'],\n",
        "    row['Delivery_location_latitude'],\n",
        "    row['Delivery_location_longitude']\n",
        "), axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Drop useless columns\n",
        "df.drop(['day_of_week','Vehicle_condition',\n",
        "         'Order_Date','Time_Orderd','Time_Order_picked',\n",
        "         'Restaurant_latitude', 'Restaurant_longitude',               # Drop latitudes and longitudes to avoid multicollinearity\n",
        "         'Delivery_location_latitude', 'Delivery_location_longitude'], axis=1, inplace=True)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Final feature set\n",
        "features = [\n",
        "    'distance_km',\n",
        "    'order_hour',\n",
        "    'is_weekend',\n",
        "    'Weather_condition',\n",
        "    'Road_traffic_density',\n",
        "    'Delivery_person_Age',\n",
        "    'Delivery_person_Ratings',\n",
        "    'Festival',\n",
        "    'multiple_deliveries',\n",
        "    'City'\n",
        "]\n",
        "\n",
        "target = 'Time_taken_log'\n",
        "X = df[features]\n",
        "y = df[target]\n",
        "\n",
        "df.columns\n"
      ]
    },

      ],
      "source": [
        "# Train / Validation / Test split with stratified binning\n",
        "\n",
        "# First split: Train+Val vs Test\n",
        "X_temp, X_test, y_temp, y_test, bins_temp, bins_test = train_test_split(\n",
        "    X,\n",
        "    y,\n",
        "    df['target_bins'],\n",
        "    test_size=0.15,\n",
        "    random_state=42,\n",
        "    stratify=df['target_bins']\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Second split: Train vs Val\n",
        "X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(\n",
        "    X_temp, y_temp,\n",
        "    test_size=0.17647,  # gives 12.75% val\n",
        "    random_state=42,\n",
        "    stratify=bins_temp   # stratify using temp bins\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Train / Val / Test sizes:\", X_train.shape[0], X_val.shape[0], X_test.shape[0])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Drop target_bins and Time_taken_log from split datasets\n",
        "X_train = X_train.drop(columns=[\"target_bins\", \"Time_taken_log\"], errors='ignore')\n",
        "X_val   = X_val.drop(columns=[\"target_bins\", \"Time_taken_log\"], errors='ignore')\n",
        "X_test  = X_test.drop(columns=[\"target_bins\", \"Time_taken_log\"], errors='ignore')\n",
        "\n",
        "# No longer needed after splitting\n",
        "df.drop(columns=['target_bins'], inplace=True)"
      ]
    },

      "source": [
        "# Create DMatrix objects\n",
        "dtrain = xgb.DMatrix(X_train, label=y_train)\n",
        "dval = xgb.DMatrix(X_val, label=y_val)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define XGBoost parameters\n",
        "params = {\n",
        "    'objective': 'reg:squarederror',\n",
        "    'max_depth': 3,\n",
        "    'learning_rate': 0.1,\n",
        "    'subsample': 0.8,\n",
        "    'colsample_bytree': 0.8,\n",
        "}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create EarlyStopping callback\n",
        "early_stop = xgb.callback.EarlyStopping(\n",
        "    rounds=10,\n",
        "    metric_name='rmse',\n",
        "    data_name=\"validation_0\",\n",
        "    save_best=True,\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Train model with early stopping\n",
        "model = xgb.train(\n",
        "    params,\n",
        "    dtrain,\n",
        "    num_boost_round=1000,\n",
        "    evals=[(dtrain, \"train\"), (dval, \"validation_0\")],\n",
        "    callbacks=[early_stop],\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Make predictions and evaluate performance\n",
        "y_pred = model.predict(dval)\n",
        "rmse = root_mean_squared_error(y_val, y_pred)\n",
        "print(f\"Final RMSE: {rmse:.3f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Best iteration: {model.best_iteration}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Best score: {model.best_score}\")"
      ]
    },

        "# Evaluate on test set (business metric: MAE in minutes)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create DMatrix for the test set  using X_test as input for the model\n",
        "dtest = xgb.DMatrix(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Make predictions on the test set  the model predicts the Time_taken values based on X_test\n",
        "y_pred = model.predict(dtest)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Evaluate the model using MAE, RMSE, and R\n",
        "\n",
        "# MAE: Mean Absolute Error between the true values y_test and the predicted values y_pred\n",
        "mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "# RMSE: Calculates the Root Mean Squared Error (penalizes large errors more)\n",
        "rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))\n",
        "\n",
        "# R: Measures how much of the variance in y_test is explained by the model\n",
        "r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Print model performance metrics on the test set  final values on the test data\n",
        "print(\"\\nModel performance on TEST set:\")\n",
        "print(f\"MAE  : {mae:.3f} minutes\")     # Mean Absolute Error in minutes\n",
        "print(f\"RMSE : {rmse:.3f} minutes\")    # Root Mean Squared Error in minutes\n",
        "print(f\"R   : {r2:.3f}\")              # Coefficient of Determination (R) (01)\n"
      ]

        "\n",
        "# Metrics BEFORE tuning\n",
        "mae_before = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_before)\n",
        "rmse_before = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_before))\n",
        "r2_before = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_before)\n",

        "print(f\"RMSE : {rmse_before:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R   : {r2_before:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"MAPE : {mape_before:.2f}%\")\n",
        "print(f\"Train MAE : {train_mae_before:.3f}\") # Display Train MAE"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Wom7tYsCbGoZ"
      },
      "source": [
        "**Model Performance Discussion**\n",
        "\n",
        "- MAE (Mean Absolute Error) indicates the average prediction error in minutes.\n",
        "- RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) penalizes larger errors.\n",
        "- R Score shows how much variance in delivery time the model explains.\n",
        "\n",
        "Higher R and lower MAE/RMSE reflect better performance."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 31,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "bxHo0HTBrbgr",
        "outputId": "cd55d2f1-c3fe-4cb9-b209-4bd36dc5924e"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "\n",
            " Cross-Validation MAE: 0.155\n",
            "Difference Train vs CV -> 0.001\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Overfitting Detection using Cross-validation\n",
        "\n",
        "kfold = KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a scikit-learn-compatible XGBRegressor for cross_val_score\n",
        "# Use the same parameters and the best_iteration from the trained model\n",
        "skl_xgb_model = xgb.XGBRegressor(\n",
        "    objective=params['objective'],\n",
        "    max_depth=params['max_depth'],\n",
        "    learning_rate=params['learning_rate'],\n",
        "    subsample=params['subsample'],\n",
        "    colsample_bytree=params['colsample_bytree'],\n",
        "    n_estimators=model.best_iteration + 1,  # use best_iteration as n_estimators\n",
        "    random_state=42\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "cv_scores = cross_val_score(skl_xgb_model, X, y, cv=kfold, scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error')\n",
        "cv_mae_before = -np.mean(cv_scores)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"\\n Cross-Validation MAE: {cv_mae_before:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Difference Train vs CV -> {abs(mae_before - cv_mae_before):.3f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Interpretation Tip:\n",
        "# If CV  Test -> Good generalization\n",
        "# If CV << Test -> Overfitting\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",

      ],
      "source": [
        "param_dist = {\n",
        "    \"n_estimators\": [300, 500, 800],\n",
        "    \"max_depth\": [3,4,5,6],\n",
        "    \"learning_rate\": [0.01, 0.03, 0.05],\n",
        "    \"subsample\": [0.6,0.7,0.8,0.9],\n",
        "    \"colsample_bytree\": [0.6,0.7,0.8],\n",
        "    \"min_child_weight\": [1,3,5],\n",
        "    \"gamma\": [0, 0.1, 0.3],\n",
        "    \"reg_alpha\":[0,0.1,0.5,1],\n",
        "    \"reg_lambda\":[1,1.5,2.5]\n",
        "}\n",
        "\n",
        "random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(\n",
        "    estimator=xgb.XGBRegressor(objective='reg:squarederror', random_state=42, n_jobs=-1),\n",
        "    param_distributions=param_dist,\n",
        "    n_iter=40,\n",
        "    scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error',\n",
        "    cv=3,\n",
        "    verbose=2,\n",
        "    n_jobs=-1,\n",
        "    random_state=42\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "random_search.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Best parameters and model\n",
        "print(\"Best parameters from RandomizedSearchCV:\", random_search.best_params_)\n",
        "\n",
        "best_model = random_search.best_estimator_\n",
        "y_pred_tuned = best_model.predict(X_test)\n"
      ]

          "text": [
            "\n",
            "Model Performance After Tuning\n",
            "MAE  : 0.148\n",
            "RMSE : 0.190\n",
            "R   : 0.714\n",
            "MAPE : 4.76%\n",
            "Train MAE : 0.145\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# MODEL PERFORMANCE AFTER TUNING\n",
        "y_pred_after = best_model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "y_train_pred_after = best_model.predict(X_train) # Predict on training set\n",
        "\n",
        "mae_after  = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred_after)\n",
        "rmse_after = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_after))\n",
        "r2_after   = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_after)\n",
        "mape_after = np.mean(np.abs((y_test - y_pred_after) / y_test)) * 100\n",
        "train_mae_after = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred_after) # Calculate MAE on training set\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\nModel Performance After Tuning\")\n",
        "print(f\"MAE  : {mae_after:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"RMSE : {rmse_after:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R   : {r2_after:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"MAPE : {mape_after:.2f}%\")\n",
        "print(f\"Train MAE : {train_mae_after:.3f}\") # Display Train MAE"
      ]
    },

              "      async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
              "        const element = document.querySelector('#df-41b1cbf0-21b5-462d-9688-16eb1cec1a47');\n",
              "        const dataTable =\n",
              "          await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
              "                                                    [key], {});\n",
              "        if (!dataTable) return;\n",
              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",
              "        dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
              "        await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
              "        docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
              "        element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
              "      }\n",
              "    </script>\n",
              "  </div>\n",

              "      <script>\n",
              "        async function quickchart(key) {\n",
              "          const quickchartButtonEl =\n",
              "            document.querySelector('#' + key + ' button');\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.disabled = true;  // To prevent multiple clicks.\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.classList.add('colab-df-spinner');\n",
              "          try {\n",
              "            const charts = await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction(\n",
              "                'suggestCharts', [key], {});\n",
              "          } catch (error) {\n",
              "            console.error('Error during call to suggestCharts:', error);\n",
              "          }\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.classList.remove('colab-df-spinner');\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.classList.add('colab-df-quickchart-complete');\n",
              "        }\n",
              "        (() => {\n",
              "          let quickchartButtonEl =\n",
              "            document.querySelector('#df-a6a26e3b-22c0-40ec-b886-a267a47de474 button');\n",
              "          quickchartButtonEl.style.display =\n",
              "            google.colab.kernel.accessAllowed ? 'block' : 'none';\n",
              "        })();\n",
              "      </script>\n",
              "    </div>\n",
              "\n",
              "  <div id=\"id_af4ec459-9b95-455f-b0d2-7e9e7a2dd9ef\">\n",

        "# Regression Visualizations\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. Actual vs Predicted (in minutes)\n",
        "# Convert back from log to minutes for visualization ONLY\n",
        "y_test_actual = np.expm1(y_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create DMatrix for X_test before prediction\n",
        "dtest_for_viz = xgb.DMatrix(X_test)\n",
        "y_pred_log = model.predict(dtest_for_viz)\n",
        "y_pred_actual = np.expm1(y_pred_log)\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))\n",
        "sns.scatterplot(x=y_test_actual, y=y_pred_actual, alpha=0.4)\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Actual Time Taken (min)\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Predicted Time Taken (min)\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Actual vs Predicted Delivery Time\")\n",
        "plt.plot([y_test_actual.min(), y_test_actual.max()],\n",
        "         [y_test_actual.min(), y_test_actual.max()], 'r--')\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2. Residual Distribution (LOG SCALE)\n",
        "# compute residuals in LOG SCALE\n",
        "y_test_log = y_test             # already log-transformed\n",
        "residuals_log = y_test_log - y_pred_log\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))\n",
        "sns.histplot(residuals_log, kde=True)\n",
        "plt.title(\"Residual Distribution (Log Scale)\")\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Prediction Error (log scale)\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3. Residual Plot (LOG SCALE)\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))\n",
        "plt.scatter(y_pred_log, residuals_log, alpha=0.4)\n",
        "plt.axhline(0, color='red', linestyle='--')\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Predicted (Log Scale)\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Residual (Log Scale)\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Residuals vs Predictions (Log Scale)\")\n",
        "plt.show()\n"

          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 1000
        },
        "id": "v6K0564Cj1nn",

      "outputs": [
        {

          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "<Figure size 800x600 with 1 Axes>"
            ],
            "image/png": "\n"
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Function to plot learning curve\n",
        "def plot_learning_curve(model, X, y, title):\n",
        "\n",
        "    # If the model is a native XGBoost Booster, wrap it in a scikit-learn compatible XGBRegressor\n",
        "    if isinstance(model, xgb.Booster):\n",
        "        skl_model = xgb.XGBRegressor(\n",
        "            objective=params['objective'],\n",
        "            max_depth=params['max_depth'],\n",
        "            learning_rate=params['learning_rate'],\n",
        "            subsample=params['subsample'],\n",
        "            colsample_bytree=params['colsample_bytree'],\n",
        "            n_estimators=model.best_iteration + 1,  # Use best_iteration for the wrapped model\n",
        "            random_state=42\n",
        "        )\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        skl_model = model\n",
        "\n",
        "    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(\n",
        "        estimator=skl_model,\n",
        "        X=X,\n",
        "        y=y,\n",
        "        cv=5,\n",
        "        scoring='neg_mean_absolute_error',     # MAE for regression\n",
        "        train_sizes=np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 8),\n",
        "        shuffle=True,\n",
        "        random_state=42\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "    train_scores = -train_scores\n",
        "    test_scores = -test_scores\n",
        "\n",
        "    train_mean = train_scores.mean(axis=1)\n",
        "    test_mean = test_scores.mean(axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "    plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))\n",
        "    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_mean, 'o-', label='Training Error')\n",
        "    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_mean, 'o-', label='Cross-validation Error', color='orange')\n",
        "\n",
        "    plt.title(title)\n",
        "    plt.xlabel(\"Training Set Size\")\n",
        "    plt.ylabel(\"MAE (Error)\")\n",
        "    plt.legend()\n",
        "    plt.grid(True)\n",
        "    plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "# BEFORE TUNING\n",
        "plot_learning_curve(model, X, y, \"Overfitting Graph: Before Tuning\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# AFTER TUNING\n",
        "plot_learning_curve(best_model, X, y, \"Overfitting Graph: After Tuning\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Interpretation Tip:\n",
        "# - If curves converge and flatten  Good model\n",
        "# - If large gap  Overfitting\n",
        "# - If both high  Underfitting"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 38,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "D6f8iVTeW0O_"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# Define Models for Baseline comparison\n",
        "models = {\n",
        "    \"Decision Tree Regressor\": DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42),\n",
        "    \"Random Forest Regressor\": RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42),\n",
        "    \"XGBoost Regressor\": xgb.XGBRegressor(\n",
        "        objective=params['objective'],\n",
        "        max_depth=params['max_depth'],\n",
        "        learning_rate=params['learning_rate'],\n",
        "        subsample=params['subsample'],\n",
        "        colsample_bytree=params['colsample_bytree'],\n",
        "        n_estimators=model.best_iteration + 1, # Use best_iteration from the trained Booster\n",
        "        random_state=42\n",
        "    )\n",
        "}\n",
        "\n",
        "results = []"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 39,
      "metadata": {
        "id": "_aKO9FGQa6GD"
      },
      "outputs": [],
      "source": [
        "# 2. Train, Predict, Evaluate\n",
        "for name, model in models.items():\n",
        "    model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "    mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "    rmse = np.sqrt(mse)\n",
        "    r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "    results.append({\n",
        "        \"Model\": name,\n",
        "        \"MAE\": mae,\n",
        "        \"MSE\": mse,\n",
        "        \"RMSE\": rmse,\n",
        "        \"R Score\": r2\n",
        "    })"
      ]
    },

              "        const element = document.querySelector('#df-37dd550d-4240-4d8c-bad4-d54a882ab4e7');\n",
              "        const dataTable =\n",
              "          await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
              "                                                    [key], {});\n",
              "        if (!dataTable) return;\n",
              "\n",
              "        const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
              "          '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
              "          + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
              "        element.innerHTML = '';\n",
              "        dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
              "        await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
              "        const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
              "        docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
              "        element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
              "      }\n",

            "text/plain": [
              "'\\nMODEL_PATH = \"xgb_time_taken_model.joblib\"\\n\\n# ---------- helpers ----------\\ndef haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\\n    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])\\n    dlon = lon2 - lon1\\n    dlat = lat2 - lat1\\n    a = sin(dlat/2)**2 + cos(lat1)*cos(lat2)*sin(dlon/2)**2\\n    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))\\n    return 6371 * c\\n\\ndef validate_coords(lat, lon):\\n    if not (-90 <= lat <= 90):\\n        raise ValueError(\"Latitude must be between -90 and 90\")\\n    if not (-180 <= lon <= 180):\\n        raise ValueError(\"Longitude must be between -180 and 180\")\\n\\n# mappings (case-insensitive)\\nweather_map = {\\'sunny\\': 4, \\'cloudy\\': 1, \\'stormy\\': 3, \\'windy\\': 5, \\'sandstorms\\': 2}\\ntraffic_map = {\\'low\\': 1, \\'medium\\': 2, \\'jam\\': 3}\\ncity_map = {\\'metropolitian\\': 1, \\'urban\\': 0}\\n\\n# ---------- load model ----------\\ntry:\\n    model = joblib.load(MODEL_PATH)\\nexcept Exception as e:\\n    print(\"Error loading model:\", e)\\n    raise SystemExit(1)\\n\\n# ---------- interactive inputs ----------\\nprint(\"=== Delivery Time Prediction ===\")\\ndriver_name = input(\"Driver name: \").strip()\\n\\nprint(\"\\nChoose weather: Sunny / Cloudy / Stormy / Windy / Sandstorms\")\\nweather = input(\"Weather: \").strip().lower()\\n\\nprint(\"\\nChoose traffic: Low / Medium / Jam\")\\ntraffic = input(\"Traffic: \").strip().lower()\\n\\nprint(\"\\nChoose city type: Metropolitian / Urban\")\\ncity = input(\"City: \").strip().lower()\\n\\norder_hour = int(input(\"\\nOrder hour (0-23): \"))\\nis_weekend = int(input(\"Is weekend? (0/1): \"))\\nfestival = int(input(\"Festival? (0/1): \"))\\nage = float(input(\"Driver age: \"))\\nrating = float(input(\"Driver rating (1-5): \"))\\nmultiple = int(input(\"Multiple deliveries count: \"))\\n\\nrest_lat = float(input(\"Restaurant latitude: \"))\\nrest_lon = float(input(\"Restaurant longitude: \"))\\ndest_lat = float(input(\"Destination latitude: \"))\\ndest_lon = float(input(\"Destination longitude: \"))\\n\\n# ---------- validate coords ----------\\nvalidate_coords(rest_lat, rest_lon)\\nvalidate_coords(dest_lat, dest_lon)\\n\\n# ---------- build DataFrame (base order) ----------\\ndistance = haversine(rest_lat, rest_lon, dest_lat, dest_lon)\\n\\nX = pd.DataFrame([{\\n    \"distance_km\": distance,\\n    \"order_hour\": order_hour,\\n    \"is_weekend\": is_weekend,\\n    \"Weather_condition\": weather_map.get(weather, 0),\\n    \"Road_traffic_density\": traffic_map.get(traffic, 0),\\n    \"Delivery_person_Age\": age,\\n    \"Delivery_person_Ratings\": rating,\\n    \"Festival\": festival,\\n    \"multiple_deliveries\": multiple,\\n    \"City\": city_map.get(city, 0)\\n}])\\n\\n# ---------- determine expected feature names from model ----------\\nexpected = None\\n# If model is sklearn wrapper XGBRegressor\\ntry:\\n    if hasattr(model, \"get_booster\"):\\n        expected = model.get_booster().feature_names\\nexcept Exception:\\n    expected = None\\n\\n# If model is raw Booster loaded\\nif expected is None and hasattr(model, \"feature_names\"):\\n    expected = model.feature_names\\n\\n# fallback to feature_names_in_ (sklearn attr)\\nif expected is None and hasattr(model, \"feature_names_in_\"):\\n    expected = list(model.feature_names_in_)\\n\\n# Convert to list if it\\'s not None\\nif expected is not None:\\n    expected = list(expected)\\n\\n# ---------- reorder X to match expected (or error nicely) ----------\\nif expected:\\n    set_expected = set(expected)\\n    set_X = set(X.columns.tolist())\\n    if set_expected.issubset(set_X):\\n        # keep only expected columns and reorder\\n        X = X[expected]\\n    else:\\n        missing = set_expected - set_X\\n        extra = set_X - set_expected\\n        print(\"Feature mismatch detected.\")\\n        if missing:\\n            print(\"Missing features expected by model:\", missing)\\n        if extra:\\n            print(\"Extra features in input (will be ignored):\", extra)\\n        print(\"Please ensure your input features match the model\\'s training features.\")\\n        raise SystemExit(1)\\n# If we don\\'t know expected, proceed with current X (best-effort)\\nelse:\\n    print(\"Warning: could not read model.feature_names. Proceeding with current feature order.\")\\n\\n# ---------- predict (handle Booster and wrapper) ----------\\ntry:\\n    # try sklearn-style predict first\\n    y_log = model.predict(X)\\nexcept TypeError:\\n    # likely raw Booster -> use DMatrix with feature_names if we have them\\n    try:\\n        if expected:\\n            dmat = xgb.DMatrix(X, feature_names=expected)\\n        else:\\n            dmat = xgb.DMatrix(X)\\n        y_log = model.predict(dmat)\\n    except Exception as e:\\n        print(\"Prediction failed:\", e)\\n        raise SystemExit(1)\\nexcept Exception as e:\\n    print(\"Prediction failed:\", e)\\n    raise SystemExit(1)\\n\\n# ---------- postprocess ----------\\ny = np.expm1(np.array(y_log).ravel())[0]\\n\\nprint(\"\\n==============================\")\\nprint(f\"Driver: {driver_name}\")\\nprint(f\"Distance (km): {distance:.3f}\")\\nprint(f\"Predicted delivery time: {y:.2f} minutes\")\\nprint(\"==============================\")\\n'"

            "application/vnd.google.colaboratory.intrinsic+json": {
              "type": "string"
            }
          },
          "metadata": {},
          "execution_count": 42
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# predict_fix_feature_names.py\n",
        "\"\"\"\n",
        "MODEL_PATH = \"xgb_time_taken_model.joblib\"\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- helpers ----------\n",
        "def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\n",
        "    lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = map(radians, [lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])\n",
        "    dlon = lon2 - lon1\n",
        "    dlat = lat2 - lat1\n",
        "    a = sin(dlat/2)**2 + cos(lat1)*cos(lat2)*sin(dlon/2)**2\n",
        "    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))\n",
        "    return 6371 * c\n",
        "\n",
        "def validate_coords(lat, lon):\n",
        "    if not (-90 <= lat <= 90):\n",
        "        raise ValueError(\"Latitude must be between -90 and 90\")\n",
        "    if not (-180 <= lon <= 180):\n",
        "        raise ValueError(\"Longitude must be between -180 and 180\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# mappings (case-insensitive)\n",
        "weather_map = {'sunny': 4, 'cloudy': 1, 'stormy': 3, 'windy': 5, 'sandstorms': 2}\n",
        "traffic_map = {'low': 1, 'medium': 2, 'jam': 3}\n",
        "city_map = {'metropolitian': 1, 'urban': 0}\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- load model ----------\n",
        "try:\n",
        "    model = joblib.load(MODEL_PATH)\n",
        "except Exception as e:\n",
        "    print(\"Error loading model:\", e)\n",
        "    raise SystemExit(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- interactive inputs ----------\n",
        "print(\"=== Delivery Time Prediction ===\")\n",
        "driver_name = input(\"Driver name: \").strip()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\nChoose weather: Sunny / Cloudy / Stormy / Windy / Sandstorms\")\n",
        "weather = input(\"Weather: \").strip().lower()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\nChoose traffic: Low / Medium / Jam\")\n",
        "traffic = input(\"Traffic: \").strip().lower()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\nChoose city type: Metropolitian / Urban\")\n",
        "city = input(\"City: \").strip().lower()\n",
        "\n",
        "order_hour = int(input(\"\\nOrder hour (0-23): \"))\n",
        "is_weekend = int(input(\"Is weekend? (0/1): \"))\n",
        "festival = int(input(\"Festival? (0/1): \"))\n",
        "age = float(input(\"Driver age: \"))\n",
        "rating = float(input(\"Driver rating (1-5): \"))\n",
        "multiple = int(input(\"Multiple deliveries count: \"))\n",
        "\n",
        "rest_lat = float(input(\"Restaurant latitude: \"))\n",
        "rest_lon = float(input(\"Restaurant longitude: \"))\n",
        "dest_lat = float(input(\"Destination latitude: \"))\n",
        "dest_lon = float(input(\"Destination longitude: \"))\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- validate coords ----------\n",
        "validate_coords(rest_lat, rest_lon)\n",
        "validate_coords(dest_lat, dest_lon)\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- build DataFrame (base order) ----------\n",
        "distance = haversine(rest_lat, rest_lon, dest_lat, dest_lon)\n",
        "\n",
        "X = pd.DataFrame([{\n",
        "    \"distance_km\": distance,\n",
        "    \"order_hour\": order_hour,\n",
        "    \"is_weekend\": is_weekend,\n",
        "    \"Weather_condition\": weather_map.get(weather, 0),\n",
        "    \"Road_traffic_density\": traffic_map.get(traffic, 0),\n",
        "    \"Delivery_person_Age\": age,\n",
        "    \"Delivery_person_Ratings\": rating,\n",
        "    \"Festival\": festival,\n",
        "    \"multiple_deliveries\": multiple,\n",
        "    \"City\": city_map.get(city, 0)\n",
        "}])\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- determine expected feature names from model ----------\n",
        "expected = None\n",
        "# If model is sklearn wrapper XGBRegressor\n",
        "try:\n",
        "    if hasattr(model, \"get_booster\"):\n",
        "        expected = model.get_booster().feature_names\n",
        "except Exception:\n",
        "    expected = None\n",
        "\n",
        "# If model is raw Booster loaded\n",
        "if expected is None and hasattr(model, \"feature_names\"):\n",
        "    expected = model.feature_names\n",
        "\n",
        "# fallback to feature_names_in_ (sklearn attr)\n",
        "if expected is None and hasattr(model, \"feature_names_in_\"):\n",
        "    expected = list(model.feature_names_in_)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Convert to list if it's not None\n",
        "if expected is not None:\n",
        "    expected = list(expected)\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- reorder X to match expected (or error nicely) ----------\n",
        "if expected:\n",
        "    set_expected = set(expected)\n",
        "    set_X = set(X.columns.tolist())\n",
        "    if set_expected.issubset(set_X):\n",
        "        # keep only expected columns and reorder\n",
        "        X = X[expected]\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        missing = set_expected - set_X\n",
        "        extra = set_X - set_expected\n",
        "        print(\"Feature mismatch detected.\")\n",
        "        if missing:\n",
        "            print(\"Missing features expected by model:\", missing)\n",
        "        if extra:\n",
        "            print(\"Extra features in input (will be ignored):\", extra)\n",
        "        print(\"Please ensure your input features match the model's training features.\")\n",
        "        raise SystemExit(1)\n",
        "# If we don't know expected, proceed with current X (best-effort)\n",
        "else:\n",
        "    print(\"Warning: could not read model.feature_names. Proceeding with current feature order.\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- predict (handle Booster and wrapper) ----------\n",
        "try:\n",
        "    # try sklearn-style predict first\n",
        "    y_log = model.predict(X)\n",
        "except TypeError:\n",
        "    # likely raw Booster -> use DMatrix with feature_names if we have them\n",
        "    try:\n",
        "        if expected:\n",
        "            dmat = xgb.DMatrix(X, feature_names=expected)\n",
        "        else:\n",
        "            dmat = xgb.DMatrix(X)\n",
        "        y_log = model.predict(dmat)\n",
        "    except Exception as e:\n",
        "        print(\"Prediction failed:\", e)\n",
        "        raise SystemExit(1)\n",
        "except Exception as e:\n",
        "    print(\"Prediction failed:\", e)\n",
        "    raise SystemExit(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# ---------- postprocess ----------\n",
        "y = np.expm1(np.array(y_log).ravel())[0]\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\n==============================\")\n",
        "print(f\"Driver: {driver_name}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Distance (km): {distance:.3f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Predicted delivery time: {y:.2f} minutes\")\n",
        "print(\"==============================\")\n",
        "\"\"\""
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "q1ETSbgWwsVW"

      "source": [
        "###  Model Performance Insights\n",
        "\n",
        "After comparing the three baseline models (Decision Tree Regressor, Random Forest Regressor, and XGBoost Regressor), we can summarize the following insights:\n",
        "\n",
        "- XGBoost Regressor performs the best overall, achieving the lowest MAE/RMSE and the highest R score.  \n",
        "  This means XGBoost produces the most accurate predictions and explains more variance in the target variable.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Random Forest Regressor performs better than a single Decision Tree.  \n",
        "  This improvement is expected because Random Forest uses multiple trees and averages their results, reducing overfitting.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Decision Tree Regressor has the weakest performance among the three models.  \n",
        "  It shows higher prediction errors and lower R, indicating that single-tree models struggle with complex or noisy real-world data.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Based on the metrics and visual comparisons, XGBoost is clearly the most suitable final model for this project."

This aligns with modern XGBoost API usage.\n"
      ]

      "source": [
        "## Summary:\n",
        "\n",
        "### Data Analysis Key Findings\n",
        "*   The primary task involved refactoring the XGBoost training procedure to replace the deprecated `early_stopping_rounds` parameter with the `xgb.callback.EarlyStopping` callback.\n",
        "*   The `monitor` argument for the `EarlyStopping` callback was specifically set to 'validation_0-mae' to track the Mean Absolute Error on the validation set.\n",
        "*   The refactored code now passes the `EarlyStopping` callback within a `callbacks` list to the `fit` method of the XGBoost model, aligning with contemporary API usage.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Insights or Next Steps\n",
        "*   This refactoring ensures that the XGBoost training code adheres to the most current and recommended API practices, improving code robustness and future compatibility.\n",
        "*   Moving forward, this standardized approach allows for easier integration of other advanced XGBoost callbacks, enabling more sophisticated training monitoring and control.\n"
